{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_cartier_ver01/data/sn94060041/00542866779/1930012501/0059.xml":{"full_text":"CHANGES IN NOR\nTHAMPTON COUNTY\nOld Home Prize Essay. Frank-'\ntown-Nassawadox H. S. Writ\nten By Edith Sparrow\nA\u00bbs far as we can look back in the j\nhistory of mankind changes have:\ndeveloped. Some people believe,!\nhowever, the present is offering us'\nmore positive changes than has any;\nother period. Let us observe some;\nof these in Northampton County. i:\nWhen our ancestors, English gen-1\ntlonren, first settled in Northamp\nton, they built their large colonial.\nhomes. These were filled with ser-j\nvants or 'slaves. As we travel]'\nthrough the county today we see_ a\nfew of these homes standing as re\nminders of the past. Vauclause an j\nthe Globe are good examples. i,\nToday the?? home? seem impracti-\ncal to us. We have small families,\nfew servants and few guests to en-J\ntertain. Homes are smaller and i\nmore convenient. We find in th1 j\nhomes many new inventions. The t\nhousewife has to aid her the many 1\nnew devices electricity has made i\npossible, such as the vacuum cleaner.j]\nsewing machine, gas range and frig-\nidaire. These are great conveniences. 1\noffer many comforts and require at-\ntention and care unknown to the\nold type of servant.\n'Alien our grandmothers and great-'1\ngrandmothers wished for entertain\nment they gathered in private homes\nand played games and danced. These\nwere mild domestic forms of enter-\ntainment where the spirit of home\nand good fellowship reigned su\npreme. j\nToday people are attracted to -t\nbeaches or theatres. Beaches are f\noffering sports and diversions which t\nmust be paid for in dollars and r\ncents. The owners are offering these\nfrom an economic standpoint rather i\nthan consideration to moral influ-\nences. Where life is free and gay i\nand moral responsibility is not defi-\nnitely placed we can hardily hope to\nfind the most wholesome influences, t\nExcellent examples of such lurid ami i\nfree life are offered, to us by some\nof the popular summer resorts.\nOur beaches are just beginning to\n\u25a0develop. Silver Beach and Wilkin?\nBeach are presenting their pastimes.\nThey resemble the larger resorts in\na way but are just laying the four.-\ndationd for their growth. The di-.\nreciion of their growth should be cf\ninterest and concern to all Eastern!(\nShoremen.\nIt would be a pleasant task to\nobserve the number of tourists who;\npass daily on the state highway.\nThe difference of the numbers of\nthe present day and several years\nago no doubt would be striking. It\nis impossible to get the exact num\nber of tourists who passed through\nour county or. any single clay several\nyears ago. However, we know that\nthe number was very small.\nIn contrast to this we find by\ncareful check in a twelve hour per\niod in May, 1929, 1158 touring cars\npassed through our county.\nA keen nutm can grasp a tv;aut:iui\nrelationship between himself r.nd the\ntourists. The tie that binds us to\nthe visitors from different parts of\n\u25a0our country should be the tie of\ndemocracy.\nThere a: e others, who also find\nenjoyment in touring. Our own resi\ndents take as much interest ir.\nacquainting- themselves with places\nof natural interest ns do the tourists\nwho visit us.\nThe fa!', and winter season seems\nto suit our people best for traveling.\nAnd Florida, Niagara Falls, Canada\nand New York are among the most\npopular places we visit. A person\nbecomes only partially aequairte 11\nwith a place or people by reading.\n:;>f them. Traveling is really neces-|\nr.nry to understand persons or places.\nThe statement, \u201cTraveling is an\neducation,\" seems to be very true,\nin the much going and coining may\nbe found real evidence of profound\nchange within our national life.\nAs we look back over our past\nhistory apparently some of the dis\nadvantages which confronted our peo\nple were lack of sufficiently strong\norganization for progress building\nand lack of interest and co-opera\ntion.\nToday we find these disadvantages\nreplaced by such helpful organiza\ntions as the Chambers of Commerce.\nThis organization was established in\nthe year 1925. Its first president,\nMr. Ben T. Gunter, and all who\nworked for this organization, were\nforerunners for the interest of the\ntwo counties. People were enthusi\nastic over the organization in its be\nginning. Its first membership wa\none thousand three hundred ninety\nthree. Seven hundred of truss mem\nbers failed in the financial suppor\nof the organization in the years o\n192f> and 1927. This seriously yr\ntarded its growth, hut with a fev\nunceasing supporters progress ha\n-been remarkable.\nThe main objects of this organi\nnation are to advert-e and publicis\nthe Eastern Shore of Virginia extern\nlively, to increase the number o\ntourists, to help mat's't more sue\n.\u2022essfully farm products, to cxicn\nuid to local communities and loci\n(organizations, and to improve tran.\nT> rtation.\nAll of a. know something of v.1\nextensive advertising by the Char\nher of Commerce of our agrieultur\nproducts and seafoods, of its influ-;\nMice in securing better hotels, inns\nmd tea rooms for accommodating\nrourists, of its petition before the\nVirginia State Highway Commission\n'or the rapid completion of the state\nHighway anii of its very important\neducational campaign for sanitary\nmprovement of the food products of\n;he peninsula. Surely with such an\norganization as the Chamber of Com\nnerce to aid us, improvement and\nlevelopment will continue.\nPoultry raising in our county has\nsttracted wide attention. Only a few\n,-oars ago poultry was thought of as\nsource of food supply for family\nAt present we find a large number\npoultry farms distributed through\n>ut the county. They are being\nmilt in sizes to accommodate hun\nIre.ls cad thousands of birds and\n\u25a0quipped with the most modem eon\neniences. Generally they are stock\nd with pure bred poultry for both\n\u25a0ggs and meat production. There\nire now several hatcheries on th\u00b0\nihore. with several thousand capac\nty, but these do not nearly supply\nhe demands for chicks. One excel\nent evidence of the decided interest\nn poultry as an industry has been\nresented in our school fair for the\nlast few years, culminating in the\nnest exhibit of poultry ever made\na this county in the fall of 192S\n.\u2019hen there were more than SO in\nividun! or croup exhibits of several\nifferent kinds of fine quality.\nAnother ard probably stronger evi\nenee is the agriculture hoys project\n,-ork in this school which shews the\nap'd iucrea-e cf poultry raising. In\nhe session of 1920-27, 3071 of the\noys took project work in poultry\nnd S0rr in potatoes. In the ses\nion of 1927-28, 44w of the boys\nook project work in poultry and\n6r; in potatoes. But in the pres\net school session 73r<- of the hoys\nre carrying- Cn poultry projects an\n0r' potatoes. Thus in 3 years the\nTterest in poultry has increased ap\niroxiinr.tely 150'' while the interest\na project work in potatoes has\nlightly decreased.\nIt is of interest to further note\nhat the returns on each dollar spent\nn poultry project work 3 years ago\nrore $1.S3. While at the same time\nhe returns in the potato project\ncork were SI.SO. But considering\nlie year cf 1927-28 the returns in\nhe poultry project work were SI.SI,\nchile in the potata project work the\n\u25a0etums on each dollar expended were\ni little less than SI.00.\nFrom this data we can see +hst\njoultry has gained a place of inter\nest in our \"imiL \u201dty a d from pro-\n:nt indications it will stand out\nircr.iinertly i the future in our\nndustrial activites.\nIn the writing of this essay I\nlave tried to consider a few of the\nnost apparent and v'-tanding\n-hanges that are taking pi. -e on\n;he Fastern Shore. I \u2018hose no doubt\n\u25a0ve can find suggest' of deeper\nmil more hidden chan; than are\n:?.king place in the in life of\nlur people which indicate the onward\nnovement of life current this\nnovement ever be for thirw-- better,\njner and more worthwhile.\nGreat Career irZarred\nby Greed and Pride\nThe earl of Marlborough, Jolm\nChurchill, died in 1722.\n\u201cFaithful, though unfortunate\u2019\u2019 runs\nthe motto beneath the due-al shield of\nMarlborough; hut you could hardly\napply either term to John Churchill,\nfounder of the fupiily fortunes.\nFaithful? lie intrigued with Wil\nliam when James was on the throne.\nHe intrigued with Janies when Wil\nliam was on the throne. Unfortu\nnate? lie earned more rewards, prob\nably, than ever fell to a subject. \u201cHe\nwas covetous us h\u201411,\u201d says Swift,\n\u201cand ambitious as the prince of it.\u201d\nEven Queen Anne had to turn aside\nand laugh when he denied it. And\nthere seems little doibt that, among\nhis other fruits of office, he did re\nceive \u00a3G,(XX) a year for placing the\narray's bread contract in the right\nhands.\nNone the less, no soldier of his age\ncould stand against him. \u201cHe never\nbesieged a town which he did not\ntake, nor fought a battle he did not\ngain,\u201d as Tenison once said in a ser\nmon.\nNot without reason his name is\nwritten in letters of gold\u2014with only\none other, that of Milton\u2014on the\nwalls of St. Paul's, his old school;\nwhere, as readers of Thackeray will\nremember, he was a schoolfellow of\nthe lovable Henry Esmond.\u2014From the\nContinental Edition of the London\nDaily Mail.\nRecollections\nAn absent-minded man called upon\n1 nis equally absent-minded doctor, and\ni ikey spent a pleasant evening togeth\ner. playing chess and exchanging po-\nlitioal views.\nFinally came the hour of parting,\nand the visitor exclaimed:\n\"You know, doctor, 1 came here spe-\ndally for something. Oh, yes, now I\nrecall it. Our maid has fainted and\nwe want you to see tier right away.\"\n\u201cThat reminds me,\" replied the doc\ntor. \u201cYour wife wanted you on the\ntelephone a while ago. The maid lias\npassed away.\"\nA Wave Is a \u2018Sea\u201d\nTiie term \"sea\u201d and \u201cseas\u201d lias a\nvariety oi uses. A sailor never says\nI \"wave\u201d or \u201cwaves,\" lie speaks of\nf j 'seas.\" A sea may be rolling toward\nyou\u2014that is a \"bead sea.\u201d One at the\nI side is a \"beam sea\": then tlie ship\nroils. Ami a sea coining up astern is\n\u2018la \u201cfollowing sea\u201d; then your ship\nj tosses, and it is a paint of debate\n1 among sea-sick travelers which of the\nc two sons of motion\u2014rolling or pitch\ning\u2014is less agonizing.\u2014From \u201cSea\nLore,\" by Stanley Rogers.\nl\n1.1\nTree* Don\u2019t Frmt\nNotwithstanding the popular hellel\nthat trees freeze In the winter, sclett\ntitle Investigation has proved, accord\ning to a Itelle Isle forester, that they\ncannot freeze hut remain dormant\nduring the winter mtn-h like certain\nwild animals. \"Kvery day or so some\none asks about the trees freezing.\u201d\nhe said, \u201cand they seem to dottht my\nword. Sap circulation stops In the\nwinter and the cells remain Inactive.\nThe sap congeals and prevents freez\ning else lhe tree would die. Some\ntimes frost will split a tree trunk\nopen hut this is due to contraction\nand expansion and not to freezing.\u201d\n\u2014Detroit News\nAid* to Cowl Greeting\nOne nt the prized curios found occa\nsionally iu Knglaud is the once popu\nlar hand cooler. These Implements\nwere spheroids of clear glass and\nwere used InO years ago hy society\nfavorites who considered It necessary\nto have their hands cool when the gal\nlant men henr low and kissed the fair\none's hand in greeting If the lady\nhad one of flie cool glass halls in her\nhand, which was extended to cover the\nnail, she was supposed to he meeting\nlire highest demands of social correct\nuoss Some of the halls were striped\nin colors to contone with milady's ci)8\nItiTtii-. Detroit Nows\nGuam\u2019s Forest Acres\nOn the island of Guam, tlie largest\nand most thickly populated of the\nMarianas, there are about li.4(Hi aeres\nof forest. A tree known as itil. hard\nand heavy at the center, is the most\nimportant wood on the island. It\nmakes very sturdy furniture and is\nbeautiful wlten kept highly polished.\nf\nDR. RICHARD RANDOLPH\nNEVITTE PASSES AWAY\nFRIDAY, JANUARY 17TH\nContinued from page 1\ni throughout the entire Eastern Shore\nj of Virginia and the three lower\ncounts of Maryland. He was prom*\ninent in fraternal organizations, be\ning a Past Master of Temperanceville\nLodge, No. 121 A. F. A. M.,\nGrand District Deputy for the Odd\nFellows of the Eastern Shore, past\nExalted Ruler of the Crisfield Md.,\nLodge of Elks, Past Councillor Tem\nperanceville Council No. 139 Jr. O.\nU. A. M. and Eastern Star. Last\nsummer he represented the Crisfield\nLodge of Elks at the Convention in\nLos Angeles, California.\nWhile Dr. Nevitte enjoyed a large\npractice, he found time to identify\nhimself with the business men of the\ncounty being a member of the Board\nof Directors of the Hailwood Nation\nal Bank and the Eastern Shore of\nVirginia Chamber cf Commerce.\nHe will be missed not only in his\nown community where he tqck an\nactive part in everything looking to\nthe uplift of it, but throughout this\nwhole section. He was a gifted\nspeaker and was in demand for all\noccasions where a speaker was .reed\ned.\nThe large attendance at his funer\nal arrd beautiful flowers attested the\nestemr in which he was held.\nMeet All Prices\u2014fancy fresh beef\n19c up. See adv. page 3.\nA. H. G. Mears,\nWachapreague, Va.\nWho Said a Man Didn\u2019t Know\nWhen He Saw One\nWe stand ready to refute that statement for already\nmen have bought three times as many suits and overcoats\nfrom us during the- first twenty days of this January as\nduring the entire rue nth a year ago.\nRight Now\nIS THE FINEST TIME IN THE WORLD MEN\nTO BUY A NEW OVERCOAT\nOR AN EXTRA SUIT\nOR BOTH\nWe are handing out phenomenal bargains and there\nwill be no let up in the big demand for them any time\nsoon. We have plenty of suits and overcoats to choose\nfrom and for two or three weeks yet we\u2019ll be busy fitting\nmen who know a bargain when they see it. But it\u2019s \u2018.he\npait of wisdom not to delay.\n8 Overcoats At Half Price\nIn this group are some of the finest coats \\ve ever\nhad. Choice of plain colors or fancies, and light or heavy\nweight as may be desired. Here are the exact sizes and\nprices in this group.\nSizes 35 36 37\n815.00\n18.00\n38\n1\n39 40\n19.75\n25.00\n27.50\n1\n2\n2\n1\nl\nNow 7.50\nNow 9.00\nNow 9.88\nNow 12.30\nNow 13.75\n28.50\n30.00\nNow 14.25\nNow 15.00\n32.50\nNow 16.25\n35.00\n37J30\nNow 17.50\nNow 18.75\nThere Are63 More Overcoats\nIn a choice selection of materials and styles all\npriced to please you in a big way. Choose them now at\nthese low prices for values that were up to $40.00.\n$16.50 $19.75\n$23.75 $27.50 $29.75\nA Great Group of\n67 Men\u2019s Suits\nWITH TWO PAIRS TROUSERS\nFine worsteds and woolens in medium and dark fancies\n$19.75 $23.75 $26.75\nwere to $28 were to $35 were to $40\nTHE STORE OF GREATEST VALUES\nESTABLISHED 36 YEARS\nCape Charles Virginia\nMAYTAG REPORTS\nRECORD BUSINESS\nFOR DECEMBER\nThe Maytag- Company, Newton\nIowa, manufacturers of the Mayta;\nAluminum Washer, reports that th<\nvolume of ileliveries for December\n1!)2!), was one of the greatest it\nMaytag history. December, which ii\nnormally not a peak month, showet\nI a market! Increase over both October I\nand November1 and brings to a close\ni a rscordbrcaking year for Maytag.\nThe outstanding prosperity of The\ni Maytag Company is significant in\nthat their product is sold through a\nj sales organization of over nine thous\nand who sell direct by demonstration'\nto the housewife. Their exceptional\ni sales volume reflects the fundamen-1\n1 tally sound business conditions exist- I\ning at the present time.\nThe Maytag organization is looking\nforward to avstill larger business in\n1930. The business outlook is good\nin every sectirn of the country and\nthe outlook in agricultural regions is\nparticularly promising.\nLet us submit you samples of\nengraved or printed wedding an\nnouncements or invitations. First\nclass work only and prompt delivery.\nPLANT LESS!\u2014MAKE MORE\nA profitable crop of Potatoes depends upon reducing the\nacreage and securing a good yield per acre.\nTherefore Plant Fewer Acres and Use\nOr Our SPECIAL 7.7-5\nWhich will insure you a good yield of Potatoes\nand a big crop of Corn.\nTilghman Co.\nFACTORIES LOCATED AT\nSalisbury, Md. Pocomoke City, Md.\nEastern Shore Banking Co.\nIncorporated\nKeller and Painter, Virginia\nCONDENSED CONSOLIDATED STATEMENT OF FINANCIAL CONDITION\nAt the Close of Business December 31, 1929\nResources\nLoans and Discounts $267,706.87\nOverdrafts 75.25\nStocks and Bonds 48,838.75\nBanking Houses and Lots 8,550.00\nFurniture and Fixtures 1,458.70\nOther Real Estate Owned 6,500.00\nj Due From Banks 86,052.27\nCash and Cash Items 6,425.10\n\nI\nT0I3I Resources \u00a7425,101.94\nLiabilities\nCapital Stock $22,600.00\nSiu-plus 57,000.00\nUndivided Profits 479.96\nDeposits 340,267.06\nCertified Checks 71.60\nCashier\u2019s Checks Outstanding 2,470.77\nReserve For Accrued Taxes 1,102.55\nDividends Unpaid 1,110.00\nTotal Liabilities\n$425,101.94\n...CERTIFICATE...\nWE HEREBY CERTIFY that we have made an examination of the books and\naccounts of the EASTERN SHORE BANKING COMPANY, INCORPORATED, KEL\nLER AND PAINTER, VIRGINIA, as at the close of business December 31, 1929, and\nhave verified therefrom the foregoing statement of resoui\u2019ces and liabilities, which, in\nour opinion, truly reflects the financial condition of the consolidated institutions as at\nDecember 31, 1929.\nRespectfully submitted,\nNorfok, Va. FREDERICK B. HILL COMPANY.\nJanuary 11th, 1930. Certified Public Accountant.\nOfficers and Directors\nOFFICERS\nA. T. HICKMAN, President\nW. B. MAPP, 1st. Vice President\nS. W. AMES, 2nd. Vice President\nC. E. NICOLLS, 3rd. Vice President\nS. D. AMES, Cashier, Keller\nW. T. ELLIOTT, Cashier, Painter\nC. A. DRUMMOND, Assistant Cashier\nW. N. DRUMMOND, Assistant Cashier\nDIRECTORS\nA. T. HICKMAN\nL. C. MEARS\nW. II. I1YSL0P\nW. B. MAPP\nJ. BROOKS MAPP\nG. T. WESCOTT\nS. W. AMES\nCHARLES T. ELMORE\nG. E. NICOLLS\nF. A. DOWNING\nDR. R. J. WHITE\nR. H. ELMORE\nI\nWe Pay 4% On Savings Deposits\nWE INVITE YOUR ACCOUNTS OUR FACILITIES ARE ADEQUATE\nSAFE DEPOSIT BOXES FOR RENT\nEastern Shore Banking Co.\nIncorporated\nKELLER, VIRGINIA\nPAINTER, VIRGINIA","height":"26748","width":"20296"}}
